### SwiftUI Introduction

SwiftUI is a declarative framework for building user interfaces across all Apple platforms. It uses a reactive, state-driven approach where you describe what the UI should do, not how to do it.

**Declarative Syntax:**

```swift
import SwiftUI

struct ContentView: View {
    var body: some View {
        VStack {
            Text("Hello, SwiftUI!")
                .font(.title)
                .foregroundColor(.blue)

            Button("Tap Me") {
                print("Button tapped")
            }
            .padding()
            .background(Color.green)
            .foregroundColor(.white)
            .cornerRadius(10)
        }
    }
}
```

**Key Concepts:**

| Concept | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| `View` | Protocol for UI elements |
| `@State` | Mutable source of truth |
| `@Binding` | Pass state to child views |
| `@ObservedObject` | Reference type observable |
| `@StateObject` | Owned observable object |
| `@EnvironmentObject` | Shared dependency injection |
| Modifiers | Chainable view configuration |

**App Structure:**

```swift
@main
struct MyApp: App {
    var body: some Scene {
        WindowGroup {
            ContentView()
        }
    }
}
```

**Key Principles:**

1. **Declarative**: Describe the UI for each state
2. **Composable**: Small views combine into complex ones
3. **Reactive**: UI automatically updates when state changes
4. **Cross-platform**: Same code works on iOS, macOS, watchOS, tvOS

```swift
// Reactive example
struct CounterView: View {
    @State private var count = 0

    var body: some View {
        VStack {
            Text("Count: \(count)")
                .font(.largeTitle)

            Button("Increment") {
                count += 1  // UI updates automatically
            }
        }
    }
}
```

> **Key Point:** SwiftUI uses a declarative paradigm. You declare what the UI should look like based on current state, and SwiftUI handles updating the display when state changes.

SwiftUI views are structs, not classes. They are lightweight and frequently recreated by the framework.

codeExample:
import SwiftUI

// Simple SwiftUI app
@main
struct HelloApp: App {
    var body: some Scene {
        WindowGroup {
            WelcomeView()
        }
    }
}

struct WelcomeView: View {
    @State private var name = ""
    @State private var showGreeting = false

    var body: some View {
        VStack(spacing: 20) {
            Text("Welcome")
                .font(.largeTitle)
                .fontWeight(.bold)

            TextField("Enter your name", text: $name)
                .textFieldStyle(RoundedBorderTextFieldStyle())
                .padding(.horizontal)

            Button(action: {
                showGreeting = true
            }) {
                Text("Greet Me!")
                    .padding()
                    .background(Color.blue)
                    .foregroundColor(.white)
                    .cornerRadius(10)
            }

            if showGreeting {
                Text("Hello, \(name.isEmpty ? "World" : name)!")
                    .font(.title2)
                    .foregroundColor(.green)
            }
        }
        .padding()
    }
}
